\title{RetailPulse Submission Report v1.5 (Single-Column)\\
\large Dashboard and Diagram Walkthrough for Submission and Presentation}
\author{Team RetailPulse}
\date{April 2026}

\begin{document}
\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
This single-column report is the presentation-ready submission narrative for RetailPulse.
It combines architecture diagrams with dashboard outputs and explains what each visual proves.
The report follows the validated five-page dashboard story: Executive Overview, Order Behavior,
Recommendations and Segments, Execution and Data Quality, and Experimental Insights and
Performance. Figures use Overleaf-friendly paths under \texttt{./Figures/image\_name}.
\end{abstract}

\section{Purpose and Submission Scope}
This document is designed for two use cases: (1) submission review and (2) presentation flow.
Instead of only showing screenshots, each figure and table includes interpretation and evidence context.
The dashboard is the primary review surface, while the notebook report pack remains the fallback.

\subsection{Validated Context}
The evidence corresponds to the validated Databricks run and Dashboard V2 packaging used in the
RetailPulse repository. The goal is to prove that the pipeline is populated, analytics outputs are
interpretable, and validation checks are reviewable.

\section{System Diagrams and Architecture Explanation}
This section explains how data moves from raw files to dashboard-ready evidence. These diagrams are
included to make the implementation logic understandable before reviewing dashboard outputs.

\subsection{End-to-End Workflow Diagram}
\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    font=\small,
    box/.style={draw, rounded corners, align=center, minimum width=3.2cm, minimum height=0.95cm, fill=blue!4},
    stage/.style={draw, rounded corners, align=center, minimum width=3.2cm, minimum height=0.95cm, fill=green!6},
    out/.style={draw, rounded corners, align=center, minimum width=3.2cm, minimum height=0.95cm, fill=orange!8},
    arr/.style={-{Stealth[length=2mm]}, thick}
]
\node[box] (sample) at (0,0) {Local Sampling\\\texttt{sample\_instacart.py}};
\node[box] (upload) at (4.2,0) {Upload to UC\\Raw Volume};
\node[stage] (bronze) at (8.4,0) {Bronze Ingest\\\texttt{02\_bronze\_ingest.py}};
\node[stage] (silver) at (12.6,0) {Silver Transform\\\texttt{03\_silver\_transform.py}};
\node[stage] (gold) at (16.8,0) {Gold Model\\\texttt{04\_gold\_model.py}};

\node[out] (olap) at (8.4,-2.2) {OLAP\\\texttt{05\_olap.py}};
\node[out] (rules) at (12.6,-2.2) {Rules \& Segments\\\texttt{06--07}};
\node[out] (ops) at (16.8,-2.2) {Streaming + Optimize\\\texttt{10--11}};

\node[out] (report) at (12.6,-4.4) {Report Pack\\\texttt{12\_report\_pack.py}};
\node[out] (dash) at (16.8,-4.4) {AI/BI Dashboard\\V2};

\draw[arr] (sample) -- (upload);
\draw[arr] (upload) -- (bronze);
\draw[arr] (bronze) -- (silver);
\draw[arr] (silver) -- (gold);

\draw[arr] (gold) -- (olap);
\draw[arr] (gold) -- (rules);
\draw[arr] (gold) -- (ops);
\draw[arr] (olap) -- (report);
\draw[arr] (rules) -- (report);
\draw[arr] (ops) -- (report);
\draw[arr] (report) -- (dash);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{RetailPulse end-to-end flow from sampling and medallion pipeline to report pack and dashboard output surfaces.}
\label{fig:endtoend}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Explanation:} Figure~\ref{fig:endtoend} shows the controlled progression from raw data to
review artifacts. The key submission value is that dashboard visuals are downstream of persisted
warehouse outputs, not ad hoc notebook cells.

\subsection{Gold-Layer Star Model Diagram}
\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    node distance=0.7cm and 1.15cm,
    dim/.style={draw, rounded corners, align=center, minimum width=2.65cm, minimum height=0.85cm, fill=purple!6},
    fact/.style={draw, rounded corners, align=center, minimum width=2.8cm, minimum height=0.95cm, fill=teal!8},
    arr/.style={-{Stealth[length=2mm]}, thick}
]
\node[dim] (du) {dim\_user};
\node[dim, below=of du] (dp) {dim\_product};
\node[dim, below=of dp] (dd) {dim\_department};
\node[dim, below=of dd] (ds) {dim\_order\_slot};

\node[fact, right=of dp] (foi) {fact\_order\_items};
\node[fact, above=of foi] (fo) {fact\_orders};
\node[fact, below=of foi] (muf) {mart\_user\_features};

\draw[arr] (du.east) -- (fo.west);
\draw[arr] (du.east) -- (foi.west);
\draw[arr] (dp.east) -- (foi.west);
\draw[arr] (dd.east) -- (foi.west);
\draw[arr] (ds.east) -- (fo.east);
\draw[arr] (ds.east) -- (foi.east);
\draw[arr] (fo.south) -- (muf.north);
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Simplified gold-layer model used for OLAP, recommendation mining, segmentation, and validation outputs.}
\label{fig:starmodel}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Explanation:} Figure~\ref{fig:starmodel} clarifies why the dashboard pages stay
consistent: most widgets are derived from stable facts/dimensions and report tables built on top of
this model.

\section{Dashboard Structure and Evidence Mapping}
The dashboard is organized into five pages. Each page has a specific analytical role and corresponding
proof artifacts.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Dashboard page map used in this report.}
\label{tab:pagemap}
\begin{tabularx}{\textwidth}{p{0.75cm} p{3.2cm} X}
\toprule
\textbf{Page} & \textbf{Name} & \textbf{What it proves} \\
\midrule
1 & Executive Overview & Core table population and high-level order behavior are visible quickly. \\
2 & Order Behavior & Basket size and demand variation are interpretable by time and product. \\
3 & Recommendations and Segments & Cross-sell rules and customer groups are actionable and explainable. \\
4 & Execution and Data Quality & Streaming replay and OLAP checks validate correctness. \\
5 & Experimental Insights and Performance & Exploratory ML and optimization evidence are available with proper caution. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabularx}
\end{table}

